      <guid>https://opguides.info/design/dacadc/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 id=&#34;analog-art-to-digital-art&#34;&gt;&#xA;  Analog Art to Digital Art&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#analog-art-to-digital-art&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;scanning-in-your-analog-art&#34;&gt;&#xA;  Scanning in your Analog Art&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#scanning-in-your-analog-art&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;[TODO] Scanner DPI, etc.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;background-removal&#34;&gt;&#xA;  Background Removal&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#background-removal&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;h3 id=&#34;via-vector-art-tools&#34;&gt;&#xA;  Via vector art tools&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#via-vector-art-tools&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h3&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Before doing this, you should know what vector art is and how it differs from the raster art you&amp;rsquo;re probably used to. I&amp;rsquo;ve talked about this a bit in the previous chapter, &#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;  &#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;a  href=&#34;https://opguides.info/design/digital/&#34;   class=&#34;book-btn design&#34;&gt;&#xA;  Digital Art&#xA;&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;. This process requires combining the two, and it&amp;rsquo;s a bit odd if you haven&amp;rsquo;t used vector art tools before.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title></title>
      <link>https://opguides.info/design/digital/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://opguides.info/design/digital/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 id=&#34;digital-art&#34;&gt;&#xA;  Digital Art&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#digital-art&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;img src=&#34;https://opguides.info/unsplash/tablet.webp&#34; alt=&#34; &#34;&gt;&#xA;&lt;p class=&#34;attribution &#34;&gt;&#xA;    Photo by &lt;a href=&#34;https://unsplash.com/@kucee&#34;&gt;cece kun&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;the-primary-tool-of-the-digital-artist-the-pen&#34;&gt;&#xA;  The primary tool of the digital artist‚Ä¶ The pen?&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#the-primary-tool-of-the-digital-artist-the-pen&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;I want to give you a heads-up that making digital art without a pen tablet or pen display of some sort is pretty awful. You can get a cheap pen tablet - they&amp;rsquo;re basically like a mouse pad that you use a pen on - for ~$30. Or you can get a fancy pen display, where you draw directly on the screen, for about ~$300 (akin to the one in the picture above but one that large is probably much more expensive)&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title></title>
      <link>https://opguides.info/design/gen/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://opguides.info/design/gen/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 id=&#34;generative-art&#34;&gt;&#xA;  Generative Art&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#generative-art&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;tip &#34;&gt;&#xA;    &lt;p&gt;AI tools, and to a lesser extend non-AI based generative art tools, have been contentious among artists for a while now. While the reasons for the apprehension vary, two common threads come up a lot:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Is it ethical, and should it be legal, to train these systems on existing images with out consent from the artists?&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;This &lt;strong&gt;way&lt;/strong&gt; out of scope for this page, but if you think no, that doesn&amp;rsquo;t exclude you from using all generative tools - most don&amp;rsquo;t use AI at all.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title></title>
      <link>https://opguides.info/design/photo/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://opguides.info/design/photo/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 id=&#34;phone-photography&#34;&gt;&#xA;  Phone Photography&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#phone-photography&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;I, for the longest time, wanted to talk about how to take photos like a professional on this page.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;I finally realized that next to nobody cares. The vast, vast majority of people just use their phone, don&amp;rsquo;t want to lug around a camera, and definitely don&amp;rsquo;t want to spend $1500 on a camera.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;More over, the best camera is the one you have. So, the phone will almost always win, at least for everything except wedding days and planned trips.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title></title>
