      <guid>https://opguides.info/design/basics/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 id=&#34;the-basics-of-art-and-design&#34;&gt;&#xA;  The Basics of Art and Design&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#the-basics-of-art-and-design&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;When you&amp;rsquo;re first learning art, every art class will beat some core ideas into your head:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Lines&lt;/strong&gt; - The &amp;lsquo;structure&amp;rsquo; bits of the works, when you start making art, you&amp;rsquo;ll often start with the Line Art&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Shape&lt;/strong&gt; - Structures that form out of lines, might appear 3D. These might be mathy, like squares, or organic, like an eye&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Form&lt;/strong&gt; - Primarily applicable to 3D (or art interpreted as 3D) - Think of this as the shape you&amp;rsquo;d see if you could move around the object in real life&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
